        ('en_EN', $$Queen of Thieves$$, $$An adventure film about a female thief planning the heist of the century in a medieval castle.$$, $$Act One: Shadows of the Past
Prologue (1358)
Ten-year-old Isabelle hides in a secret niche of the Chateau de Montfort, watching through a crack as the royal guards burst into the throne room. Her father, Count Etienne de Montfort, kneels in front of King Philippe VI. On his head is an ancient crown with sapphires, a family heirloom of the de Montfort family, which has been worn since the time of the Crusades. The king accuses the Count of conspiring with the British during the Hundred Years' War. "The crown of the traitor passes to the crown of France," the monarch proclaims, tearing the relic from the head of Isabelle's father. Three days later, the Comte de Montfort was executed on the square. Isabelle manages to escape with the help of a loyal servant, but she swears on her father's grave: "I will return what belongs to our family, even if I have to rob the king himself."
Paris, 1368
Ten years have passed. Isabelle de Montfort is now known in the criminal circles of Paris as the "Ghost" — a thief who can sneak anywhere and disappear without a trace. She lives in a slum on the Left Bank of the Seine, in a dilapidated house above the Broken Jug Tavern. She trains every morning: rope climbing, dagger wielding, lip-reading. She plans every robbery like a chess game.
Her latest case is the theft of a precious manuscript from the mansion of Cardinal Jean de Lagrange. Isabelle penetrates through the chimney using special hooks of her own design. She steals the manuscript from under the nose of the sleeping cardinal, leaving in its place a white rose, her business card. The next day, the whole of Paris is talking about the audacity of the "Ghost."
But tonight, Isabelle learns something important. In one of the stolen papers, she finds an inventory of the royal treasury of Vincennes Castle. Among the listed jewels, she sees a description: "Crown de Montfort — gold, seven sapphires, inlaid with Arabic script." Her crown. Her father's crown.
Act Two: Team Gathering
Isabelle knows she can't do it alone. Vincennes Castle is an impregnable fortress east of Paris, the residence of King Charles V the Wise. The walls are four meters thick, with a deep moat around them, and two hundred guards inside. But Isabelle de Montfort does not back down from her vows.
First Recruit: Thomas Black Claw
Thomas is the best lock picker in the kingdom, a former apprentice to the royal blacksmith. His fingers feel the slightest vibrations in the mechanisms. Isabelle finds him in the Chatelet prison, from where he is to be sent to the galleys in two days. She gets into his cell at night.
"I can get you out of here," she says. —But in return, you will open a door for me that cannot be opened."
Thomas laughs: "There are no such doors."
"The door to the royal treasury of Vincennes," Isabelle replies.
Pause. Then Thomas nods slowly. Isabelle bribes the warden, and Thomas "dies" of a fever. In fact, he is being carried out of prison in a coffin with air slots.
Second recruit: Marie Swallow
Marie is a circus acrobat and tightrope walker from Burgundy. Her troupe performs in squares, but Isabelle knows that Marie is also a pickpocket and knows how to walk on rooftops better than cats. Isabelle finds her after the performance.
"I need someone who can walk on a rope over a twenty—meter chasm," says Isabel, "in total darkness, during a thunderstorm."

Marie
hesitates, but when Isabelle shows her the outline of the robbery plan, the acrobat's eyes light up with excitement. "This is crazy," she whispers. — "I'm in."
Third recruit: Rene Thousand Faces
Rene is a master of make—up and disguise, a former mystery theater actor. He can turn a young woman into an old woman in an hour, create fake documents that are indistinguishable from the real ones. But Rene has a problem — he owes money to serious people and is hiding from creditors.
Isabelle offers him a deal: "I'll pay off your debts, and you'll turn me into a noblewoman that even the king will believe."
Rene looks at her appraisingly: "Why don't I just rob you right now?"
Isabelle smiles and in a second is behind him, holding a dagger to his throat: "Because then you won't get your share of the heist of the century."
Rene laughs and holds out her hand: "It's a deal, mademoiselle."
The fourth recruit: Jacques Grif
The most difficult recruit. Jacques de Corbeil is a former captain of the Vincennes Castle guards, who was fired for drunkenness after he lost his wife to the plague. He is bitter, disappointed and lives in poverty. Isabelle finds him in a port tavern, where he loses the last coins in a dice game.
"I know how to return your honor," she says.
"My honor died with Adele," Jacques mutters.
"Then take revenge on those who threw you away like an unnecessary rag. The king needs loyal dogs while they serve. Then they are thrown away. Help me rob Vincennes, and you'll become a legend."
Jacques stares into his wine mug for a long time. Then he asks: "The
crown that the king stole FROM  my family," Isabelle answers honestly.
Something is changing in Jacques' eyes. Perhaps he sees in her the same pain he feels himself. "Tell me the plan," he says.

Act Three: Preparation
For the next three months, the team prepares for the robbery with the precision of watchmakers.
Learning the purpose
Jacques draws detailed plans of the castle FROM  memory. Every corridor, every staircase, every secret door. He knows the changing of the guard schedule to the minute. Isabelle complements the plans with her own intelligence — she disguises herself as a laundress and enters the castle several times with laundry, memorizing the location of the guards and servants.
Thomas studies locks and mechanisms. He bribes a former blacksmith who made locks for the royal treasury, and learns that the main lock is German—made, with seven pins and a false mechanism that triggers an attempted break-in.
Marie trains on a rope stretched between the roofs, learning how to balance with a load on her back. The plan calls for her to carry the gear along a thin rope over the castle moat on a windy night.
Rene creates a new identity for Isabelle: Baroness Jeanne de Chatillon, the widow of a French knight who died in the Battle of Kassel. He makes fake letters, seals, even a mourning dress of the right cut. Isabelle learns the manners of high society, studies the genealogy of noble families, and practices a northern accent.
Introduction to the palace
Isabelle, in the guise of the Baroness de Chatillon, arrives in Vincennes with a request for an audience. She presents forged documents about donations to the church and the faithful service of her late husband. King Charles V, known for his love of educated conversation, is fascinated by a beautiful and intelligent widow who quotes Aristotle and understands astronomy.
Isabelle gets permission to stay at the castle. Every day she gains more trust by talking to the king about philosophy and politics. She is friends with the ladies of the court, plays chess with the knights, attends Mass in the castle chapel. But in fact, she counts the steps from the royal chambers to the treasury, remembers which doors creak, and studies the habits of the guards.
Meanwhile, the rest of the team takes up positions. Thomas gets a job at a blacksmith shop near the castle. Marie joins a troupe of traveling actors performing for the castle servants. Jacques, disguised as an old beggar, huddles at the castle gate, watching the changing of the guard.
Bribery and manipulation
Isabelle doesn't rely on strength alone. She manipulates people subtly. To the king's young squire, Sir Bertrand, she hints at mutual sympathy, forcing him to share information about the royal routine. To the senior lady-in-waiting, Madame de Luxembourg, she gives expensive perfumes (bought with money from previous thefts) and becomes her confidant.
The team bribes key servants. The cook receives a gold coin to put sleeping pills in the wine for the south guard tower. The laundress promises to leave the basement door unlocked. The groom will agree to keep the horses ready outside the castle wall.
But not everything is going smoothly. The royal advisor, Cardinal Guillaume de Dorman, is a shrewd and paranoid man who begins to suspect the Baroness de Chatillon. He tells his spies to check her story. Rene finds out about this in time and creates fake footprints in the archives of Paris, but there is little time left.
Act Four: The Night of the Robbery
June 23, 1368, the night of the summer solstice
The team chooses this night for a reason. A festive feast is held in the castle in honor of St. John's Day. The king and his retinue will feast until dawn, security will be relaxed, and the noise of the celebration will hide any suspicious sounds.
Phase One: Penetration (Midnight)
While the whole court is dancing and feasting, Marie, dressed as a buffoon, enters the roof of the castle under the guise of an acrobatic performance. She secures a thin cord, almost invisible in the dark, between the tower and the tree behind the moat. A thicker rope will be carried along this cord later.
Thomas and Jacques, disguised as guards (the costumes were stolen a week earlier), take up positions near the treasury. The sleeping pills begin to affect the guards of the south tower — they fall asleep right at their posts.
Isabelle absents herself during the feast, allegedly because she feels unwell. In fact, she's heading for the treasure trove. Her heart is beating like a hammer—she's been waiting for this moment for ten years.
Phase Two: Complications (1 a.m.)
But the plan begins to crumble. Cardinal de Dorman, who suffers from insomnia, notices the "sleeping" guards. He raises the alarm. The castle comes to life — the guards grab torches and swords, and the search begins.
Thomas is at the door of the treasury. His fingers are working on the German lock, but the footsteps of the approaching patrol can be heard. Jacques detains them, saying that he saw a suspicious shadow in the other wing, but it only gives a few minutes.
Click — the first pin is open. Second. Third. Sweat runs down Thomas' face. The fourth pin is stuck. The footsteps are getting closer. Fifth. Sixth.
"Hurry up!"  Jacques hisses.
The seventh pin opens with a soft chime. The door swings open just as the patrol turns the corner. Thomas and Jacques slip inside, closing the door behind them.
Phase Three: Treasure Trove (two o'clock in the morning)
Isabelle joins them in the treasure room. The room is lit by a single torch. There are chests of gold, jewels, and relics of saints along the walls. In the center is a glass showcase with royal regalia.
Isabelle sees the crown. Her crown. Seven sapphires twinkle in the torchlight. The Arabic script on the gold is a blessing inflicted by her crusader ancestor in the Holy Land. Her breath catches in her throat. She holds out her hand...
and stops.
Something's wrong. The crown looks right, but the inlay is slightly different from the one she remembers. Isabelle takes a magnifying glass (stolen earlier from the royal jeweler) and carefully examines the crown.
"It's a fake," she whispers in horror.
"What?!"  Thomas is stunned.
Isabelle thinks fast. If it's a fake, then where is the real crown? Suddenly, she remembers a conversation she had with the king a week ago. Charles V said something like, "I keep my most valuable things where I can see them every morning." She thought it was a metaphor.
"The crown is in the royal chambers," she says. — "In his private room."
Phase four: Improvisation (three o'clock in the morning)
To enter the king's private chambers when the entire castle is alerted is suicide. But Isabelle can't back down. Not now. Not when she's so close.
Jacques suggests creating a distraction. He sets fire to the stables from the windward side — the fire spreads quickly, creating panic. Half of the guards rush to put out the fire.
Marie lowers a rope from the roof to the window of the royal apartments. Isabelle, using her climbing skills, climbs up the cold stone. The wind whips her, her hands slip, but she holds on. Marie helps her climb through the window.
Isabelle finds herself in the king's bedroom. The room is luxurious: tapestries from Flanders, a four-poster bed, an astrolabe on the table. And in the corner, on a small pedestal behind glass, there is a real crown de Montfort.
She hears voices outside the door. Someone is coming. Isabelle grabs a heavy candlestick and breaks the glass. The ringing is deafening. She grabs the crown just as the door swings open.

Act Five: Face to Face with the Past
King Charles V stands in the doorway. But he's alone, unguarded. His face is calm, almost sad.
"Baroness de Chatillon," he says softly. "Or should I call you Isabelle de Montfort?"
she freezes, clutching her crown. Her hand slides to the dagger on her belt.
"I knew who you were from the day you arrived at my castle," the king continues. "You look like your father. The same eyes. The same stubborn chin."
"You killed him," Isabelle's voice is shaking with rage. "He was innocent, and you executed him to take our crown!"
"I did not kill your father," Charles says, "it was my predecessor, King Philip. I became king three years after the execution of the Comte de Montfort."
Isabelle hesitates. She knew that Charles V ascended to the throne later, but the hatred for the crown of France was so overwhelming...
"Your father was innocent," Charles continues. "I studied all the documents when I became king. He was slandered by envious people who wanted to get the lands of de Montfort. King Philip was old and sick, and he believed the false testimony."
"Then why didn't you restore my father's honor? Why didn't they return our lands?!" Isabelle screams.
"Because that would mean admitting the crown's mistake. That would weaken the government. I was a young king, France was at war with England, I needed stability. I... I chose the kingdom over justice."— Karl's voice is full of regret. — "Since then, this decision has been haunting me."
Isabelle looks at him, and for the first time sees not a monster, but a man. Tired, exhausted by the responsibility of a man who carries the burden of the crown.
"I can't give up the crown," says Karl. "It has become a symbol. If I return it to you, it will be an admission of guilt. Investigations will begin, executed nobles will receive posthumous rehabilitation, and their heirs will demand the return of their lands. The kingdom will descend into chaos."
"I don't care about your kingdom!"  Isabelle draws her dagger. "This crown is all that's left of my family!"
Karl draws his sword. He doesn't call the guards. He just pulls the blade out of its sheath.
"Then you'll have to kill me to get her," he says calmly. "I won't let myself be robbed, but I won't call the guards either. If you defeat me, the crown is yours. If I run you... I promise that your team will be able to get away with it. The King's word."
Duel
They converge in the center of the room. Isabelle is fast and agile, her style is street fighting, without rules or honor. Karl is a trained knight, his movements are precise and precise.
Their blades meet with a clang. Isabelle throws a series of quick punches, but Carl deflects them. He's stronger, but she's faster. She dodges his blow, flips over the table, dropping books and an astrolabe on the king.
Carl stumbles. Isabelle rushes forward, but he rolls over at the last moment. Her dagger plunges into the wooden floor. Carl gets up and stabs with his sword — Isabelle holds up the dagger, the blade breaks in half.
Now she only has a fragment of the blade. But she doesn't give up. They circle the room, breathing heavily. Isabelle notices that Carl is limping, an old battle wound. She starts circling to the right, forcing him to lean more on his weak leg.
Carl lunges. Isabelle steps aside and grabs a heavy tapestry from the wall. She throws it at the king, confusing him. At that moment, she hits his hand with the hilt of the broken dagger, and the sword flies out of his fingers.
Karl falls to his knees, entangled in the tapestry. Isabelle picks up his sword and puts it to his throat.
"Kill me," Carl says, looking into her eyes. "But know this: Your father wouldn't want that. Count Etienne de Montfort was a noble knight. He served France, not just the crown. He would have given his life for his country. By killing me, you will start a chaos that will kill thousands of innocent people. Is this what your father would like?"
Isabelle stands motionless. Tears are streaming down her cheeks. The sword trembles in her hands. She remembers her father—not the execution, but other moments. How he taught her to ride. How I read chivalrous novels to her. As he said: "True nobility is to protect those who are weaker than you."
She lowers her sword.
"I'm not a murderer," she whispers. "But I'm taking the crown."
Carl nods slowly. "I will not pursue you. You have an hour to leave the castle. After that, I'll rouse all the guards."
Isabelle grabs the crown and rushes to the window. Before disappearing into the night, she turns around.
"My father was right to serve France," she says. "But you were wrong not to restore his honor. Someday the truth will come out. And then history will judge you."
She disappears into the darkness.

Epilogue: The Legend
Isabelle and her team escape from Vincennes through an underground tunnel that only Jacques knew about. The fire in the stables is still burning, creating havoc. They get out of the castle walls, where horses are waiting for them.
At dawn, they reach an abandoned monastery in the forest of Fontainebleau. The team divides the loot (Isabelle has generously rewarded everyone with gold from her previous thefts), but the main prize — the crown — remains with her.
Thomas disappears to Italy, where he becomes a famous castle master. Marie opens her own circus in Avignon. Rene becomes a court painter in Burgundy. Jacques returns to military service, but now in the mercenary army, where experience is valued, not titles.
Isabelle de Montfort returns to the ruins of her father's castle. She's restoring the family chapel and putting the crown on the altar next to her father's grave.
"I got it back, Dad," she whispers. "Our honor has been restored."
But she doesn't stop. Using the remaining money, she begins a secret campaign. She bribes chroniclers to write down the truth about Count Etienne de Montfort. She hires minstrels to sing ballads about an innocent knight executed by envious enemies. Gradually, the story begins to change.
And the legend of the "Ghost" who robbed the king himself is spreading all over France. They say she's still out there somewhere, a defender of the oppressed, a thief who robs the rich and helps the poor. A white rose left at the crime scene becomes a symbol of hope.
The final scene
Ten years later, in 1378. The old King Charles V is on his deathbed. Next to him is his son, the future Charles VI. The dying king takes his son by the hand.
"When you become king," he says hoarsely, "find the file of Count Etienne de Montfort in the archives. Rehabilitate him posthumously. Give back the lands to his daughter. I... I didn't have the courage to do that in my lifetime. But you... You have to fix this injustice."
Charles VI nods, not fully understanding.
And somewhere in the Burgundy Woods, Isabelle de Montfort, now thirty-two years old, trains a new generation of orphan thieves who lost their families in the war. She teaches them not only to steal, but also to fight for justice.
On her chest, under her simple clothes, hangs a small medallion. It contains a tiny sapphire FROM  my father's crown. She sold the rest of the stones to help those in need. The crown has returned to the family chapel, but a part of it is always with Isabelle.
She looks at the sunset and smiles. The Queen of thieves has fulfilled her vow. And now he's creating a new legend—not for revenge, but for justice.
