        ('en_EN', $$Time Abyss$$, $$A thriller about a physicist who accidentally discovers time travel and confronts the paradoxes it unleashes.$$, $$Act One: Discovery
Berlin, 2024. Institute of Quantum Physics
Dr. Martin Steiner conducts the 127th experiment to create quantum decoherence. His theory is simple: if the observer's consciousness collapses the wave function, then perhaps it is possible to send consciousness back to "reconsider" this collapse.
His team is skeptical. Assistant Klara considers this to be philosophy, not science. But Martin is stubborn—his father died of a heart attack five years ago, and he's obsessed with getting a second chance.
At 23:47, the particles in the accelerator behave abnormally. An energy surge. Martin loses consciousness.
He's coming to his senses... And it's 18:30. The same day. He's in his apartment, going to work. Deja vu? No. He remembers the whole experiment, remembers how he lost consciousness at 23:47.
The first samples
Martin carefully tests the theory. He remembers the number of the passing bus — M29. Then he concentrates, as during the experiment, mentally going back five minutes. Dizziness. He's back in the same place, the bus hasn't arrived yet. In a minute, the M29.
It's working. He can jump back several hours, saving his memory.
The first use is noble: it prevents accidents by pushing the child away from the road. Then he saves the neighbor's cat, Frau Schmidt, who fell out of the window. The woman cries with gratitude: "How did you find out?!" — "Intuition," Martin smiles.
He buys a lottery ticket, remembers the numbers of the winners on TV, jumps back, buys the right ticket. 200,000 euros.
Anna, his wife, notices the changes: "Honey, you're something... strange today. Too lucky."Martin laughs it off, but understands that you need to be more careful.
Act Two: Consequences
The first cracks
A week later, Martin notices that Anna doesn't remember their anniversary. It's strange — they celebrated it three days ago. Or not? He checks the photos on his phone — there is no picture from the anniversary. But he remembers that evening: the restaurant, the red wine, her smile.
At the university, Hans's colleague looks at him warily: "Martin, are you sure you're okay? You've been like a substitute since last week. Clara avoids his gaze.
Martin checks his notes. There are no records of recent experiments in the laboratory journal. It's like they didn't exist. But there's a time machine in the lab, and he sees it.
Domino effect
Martin begins to systematically analyze the changes. Each leap back creates a "correction wave" — reality adapts to the new past, but not always predictably.
When he saved the child from an accident, the driver braked sharply, which led to another accident around the corner — three people were injured. When he won the lottery, the money did not go to the family that bought the house in the "original" line. They stayed outside.
The worst: Anna. She doesn't wear her wedding ring anymore. One evening she says, "Martin, we need to talk. I think we should live separately." He is stunned: "What? Why is that?" "You've changed. You've been like a stranger for the last few weeks."
He realizes with horror that multiple jumps have changed their relationship history. He said or didn't say something important in the past, and their love disappeared.
Correction attempt
In desperation, Martin jumps back a month, trying to find the moment where everything went wrong. But each jump changes more things. Anna has a different job in one line. In another case, they are not married at all.
He loses count of the versions of reality. Which one is the real one? The one where the father is still alive? No, the father died in all lines. Or not all of them?
Act Three: Plurality
Meeting with yourself
Martin jumps back three days and sees himself in the lab. The other Martin sees him too. They both freeze.
"Are you from the future?" — One of them asks.
"From your future. But now we're in different streams," the other replies.
They talk for three hours. The elder Martin warns: "Stop experimenting. Each jump forks reality. We are creating parallel worlds." - "But then I can return everything as it was!"— "No. You just think you're giving it back. In fact, you're creating a new branch where it looks like you've fixed it. But the original remains destroyed."
The map of realities
Martin develops a theory of parallel versions. Each jump creates a branch point. Exists:

Martin-Alpha: never invented a time machine, lives happily with Anna and two children.
Martin Beta: used a car to prevent terrorist attacks, became an adviser to the government, turned paranoid.
Martin-Gamma: learned the future of financial markets, became a billionaire, lost all his friends.
Martin-Delta: tried to save his father, accidentally caused a car accident, where Anna died. I've lost my mind.
Martin-Omega: understood the nature of time, became obsessed with the idea of control, began to manipulate history. In fact, he is the dictator of a parallel reality.

The original Martin (let's call him Martin Prime) begins to meet these versions. Some are friendly, others are hostile. Omega tries to kill him, considering him a competitor.
The price of knowledge
Martin Prime meets an Alpha version of himself who has never experimented with time. Alpha lives in an apartment with Anna. They have a son, 4 years old, and a daughter, 6 years old. They laugh at dinner.
Martin Prime watches from the shadows. Envy? Regret? He sees how he could be.
The alpha notices him: "Who are you?" —The ghost of opportunity,— Prime replies. "Are you happy?" - "Yes. And you?" Prime can't respond.
Act Four: Collapse
Collection of versions
All versions of Martin come to the conclusion at the same time: the fabric of reality is collapsing. Jumping has created so many parallel worlds that they are beginning to overlap. People see "ghosts" — themselves from other lines. Time passes erratically: seconds last for hours, days fly by in a minute.
The six Martins meet in the original laboratory (which exists in all lines). They're arguing:
Omega: "We can control all the lines! Become gods!"
Beta: "We must use this to protect humanity!"
Gamma: "Fools, this is only about survival!"
Delta (mad): "Everyone must die like she died!"
Alpha: "We must destroy the machine!"
Prime: "...Alpha is right."
The destruction plan
To destroy the time machine in all realities at the same time, a coordinated attack from all branching points is needed. But this means that all versions of Martin will disappear, except for one that existed before the first experiment.
Every Martin has to give up his existence.
Omega refuses: "I'm not going to die!" He tries to hijack the car, but the other five stop him. In the process of fighting, Delta sacrifices herself, closing the energy chain. Omega dissolves into quantum foam, shouting, "I was God!"
That leaves four: Prime, Alpha, Beta, and Gamma.

Last choice
Beta: "Which one of us will stay?"
Alpha: "Obviously. I am the only one who has never jumped. I'm the closest to the original."
Prime shakes his head, "No. I'm the original. I'm the one who started it."
Gamma: "What's the difference? We are all Martin Steiner."
They make a decision: Prime will return at the time of the first experiment. He will intentionally make a mistake that will make discovery impossible. All the branches will collapse back into one line.
Alpha holds out his hand: "Take care of them. About her. Prime nods, realizing that he is talking about Anna and the children who will never be.
Act Five: Return
23:47, the moment of the first experiment
Martin Prime materializes in the lab. His younger version stands at the control panel, ready to activate the accelerator. Prime approaches him.
Young Martin is in shock: "Who—"
"Don't ask questions. Listen carefully. You'll activate the accelerator in a minute. A crash will occur. You'll think you've discovered time travel."
"And?"
"Don't do that. Change the activation sequence. That's it." Prime shows on the panel: switch the two toggle switches in reverse order.
"But... this will ruin the whole experiment!"
"Exactly."Prime looks at himself as a young man: "You dream of a second chance. About saving my father. I dreamed too. But do you know what I've learned? There is no second chance. There are only endless branches of regrets. Save one, and you'll lose the other. Fix the past and destroy the present."
Young Martin hesitates. Prime adds, "Go home. Give Anna a hug. Tell her that you love her. That's the only time travel that matters—appreciating the moment while it's here."
Young Martin nods slowly and switches the switches.
Prime begins to dissolve: "One request... if you ever have a son... Call him Thomas. In honor of Father."
"Where are you from—" But Prime has already disappeared.
The new reality
The accelerator is activated. Sparks. Smoke. A small fire. The experiment failed. Clara runs with a fire extinguisher: "Martin! Are you okay?"
"Yes... yes, I'm fine." He looks at the charred panel. Years of work have been destroyed. Strangely, he almost feels relieved.
Martin is going home. It's 2 a.m. Anna is asleep. He carefully lies down next to her, hugs her. She mumbles sleepily, "Mm, how was the experiment?"
"Failed completely."
"Sorry, honey."
"Don't." He kisses her temple: "This is the best thing that could happen."
Epilogue: Echo
Five years later
Martin works at the university, teaches quantum mechanics. His theories about time remained unfulfilled—he didn't try again after that night.
He and Anna have two children.: son Thomas (4 years old) and daughter Emma (2 years old). They're happy.
Sometimes Martin experiences a strange deja vu. He sees a face in the crowd and thinks: "I know him," although I've never met him. He wakes up with the feeling that he has lived his whole life in a dream.
One day Thomas asks: "Dad, can I go back to the past?"
Martin thinks, "You know, son, we come back every time we remember. Memory is a time machine. But the most important thing is not to get stuck there. The past teaches us, but we live here." He tickles his son: "Here and now!"
Thomas chuckles, and Martin feels that whatever it is in parallel realities, this is the right one.
The last frame
The camera moves away from the Steiner family playing in the park. The image begins to double and triple — we see overlays of other realities.: Martin is alone, Martin is dressed as a dictator, Martin is in the laboratory, Martin is old and crazy.
All versions overlap, but gradually dissolve, leaving only one: a happy family on a sunny day.
Titles: "Time cannot be changed. You can only live."
END
$$)
) AS loc(locale, title, description, plot_summary)
ON TRUE;

