        ('en_EN', $$Songs of the Sirens$$, $$A mystical romantic drama about a young musician who falls in love with an enigmatic singer.$$, $$Act One: A Voice from the Sea
Malaga, the coastal town of Santa Lucia
Diego Ramirez, 26, plays guitar at La Perla Cafe six nights a week. Tourists clap politely and leave modest tips. His dream of a musical career has long turned into a routine. After the death of his father, a fisherman, two years ago, Diego was stuck in his hometown, helping his mother maintain the house.
One night, returning home along the coast, Diego hears singing. The voice is impossible — both human and not quite human, as if the wind and the waves are intertwined in a melody. The sound comes from the Devil's Rocks, sharp cliffs where fishermen do not swim.
Diego follows the voice. Silhouette on the highest rock: a girl in a white dress sings, looking at the moon. Her hair is blowing in the wind, and her bare feet are dangerously close to the edge of the abyss.
"Hey! Careful!" shouts Diego.
The girl turns around, scared, and... jumps. Diego rushes to the edge — there are only waves crashing on the rocks. No one. It is impossible to survive such a fall.
But the next night, the voice comes from the rocks again.
The second meeting
Diego arrives prepared: a lantern, a rope in case of rescue. The girl is there again, but this time she doesn't run away. She looks at him with huge dark eyes, wary, like a wild animal.
"Who are you?"  Diego asks.
A long pause. Then: "Marina." The accent is strange, as if she learned Spanish from old books.
"Do you live here? Why are you singing alone at night?"
"I... don't remember. I don't remember where I'm from." Her voice is shaking. "I only remember the sea and the songs."
Diego notices the details: wet hair, although it wasn't raining. The dress is made of some kind of iridescent fabric that looks like scales. She's shivering from the cold.
He takes off his jacket and drapes it over her shoulders. Marina flinches at the touch, but then gratefully wraps herself in the fabric.
"Come on, I'll walk you out. Where do you live?"
"Here. On the rocks."
“what? You're going to freeze!" Diego insists on taking her to a shelter or hospital, but Marina panics at the word "people." "No, not the crowds, please..."
They compromise: Diego brings her blankets and food, leaves her in a cave near the rocks. In return, she sings for him.
Act Two: Strange Love
Night meetings
Diego comes every night. The marina is gradually opening up. She knows songs that are hundreds of years old— old ballads that are sung only in forgotten villages. She teaches Diego melodies, and his music is transformed.
In the cafe, people say, "Diego, what's wrong with you? Your guitar is playing... otherwise. Deeper."Owner Carlos raises his salary: "So keep playing, the people are coming down!"
But Diego only cares about Marina. They talk until dawn. She's asking weird questions.: "Why are people afraid of the deep?" "How does it feel to sleep without water around?" — "What does 'house' mean?"
Diego falls in love. Marina gets attached too, but she always disappears at first light, as if she's afraid of the light.
Anomalies
Diego begins to notice oddities:
Marina never eats what he brings — bread, cheese, fruit. But when he brings raw fish (accidentally, after fishing with his uncle), she eats it greedily, without even cooking it.
She has scars on her neck, thin lines like gills. When Diego touches them, Marina screams in pain. "What is it?" "I don't know. There always have been."
One night a storm starts. Diego runs to the rocks, afraid that Marina will be washed away by the wave. But she stands at the very edge, stretching out her arms to the sea, and sings. The waves calm down around her, as if the sea is listening. Ten minutes later, the storm subsides.

Marina looks at her hands, puzzled: "I don't know. The sea... listens."
Fishermen's warnings
In a local tavern, an old fisherman, Enrique, tells a story: "I saw something in the sea last night. A woman, but not a woman—she has a tail like a fish. She sang, and the fish all swam up to her."
The others laugh, but Diego gets cold. He remembers that Marina once showed him how dolphins play near the rocks. She whistled to them, and they answered. "They told me about the currents," she said simply, as if it were normal.
Diego's mother, Dona Isabel, a strict and pious woman, warns: "Son, people say you spend nights with a strange girl on the rocks. Be careful. There are legends about sea witches in our city."
"Mom, is this superstition."
"Superstition? Your grandfather saw one. He said she almost lured his boat onto the reefs with her singing."
Act Three: The Truth
Investigation
Diego goes to the city library, run by the old senora Carla. He's looking for legends about sirens.
Carla sighs: "Are you looking for a girl on the rocks? Not the first one." She takes out an ancient book: "Chronicles of Santa Lucia, 1624."
It says: "On the full moon of September, residents heard singing from the sea. Some sailors claimed to have seen a woman with a fish tail on the reefs. The priest Father Miguel conducted an exorcism, but the singing did not stop."
Another recording, 1724: "The siren of the daughter of fisherman Juan appeared. She said that once in a century, one of their kind can become human if she finds true love before the full moon. Juan's daughter disappeared the same night, her body was found in the sea."
And the last one, 1824: "The young artist Antonio claimed to love the sea maiden. He disappeared at sea. They only found his notebook with drawings of a mermaid."
Diego thinks: 1624, 1724, 1824... the next cycle should be 1924. But it's 2024. Exactly one hundred years old.
The full moon is in two weeks.
The Revelation
Diego comes to Marina with a book: "Tell me the truth. You're one of them, aren't you? The siren."
Marina turns pale. A long silence. Then softly, "I... didn't know how to say it."
"So it's true?"
She nods. Tears are streaming down her cheeks: "I didn't mean to lie. But I was afraid you'd run away. Everyone's running away."
Diego sits, digesting the information. Then he asks: "What will happen on a full moon?"
"I have to choose. If I want to become human... forever... I need true love. Someone who will accept me, knowing the truth. But if I choose land, I will lose the sea. Forever. I will no longer be able to breathe underwater, swim with deep creatures, or hear the songs of whales. This... A part of me will die."
"And if you don't choose?"
"I'll go back to the sea. Forever. I will become what I was again, a creature of the depths. I'll forget everything.
Diego takes her hands: "Marina, I love you. It doesn't matter who you are."
"But you don't understand!" "she's crying." "My singing... It's dangerous. When I sing with full force, people lose their minds. The ships are crashing. It's not malicious intent, it's simple... That's how sirens work. We were created by the sea to protect it.
"Then don't sing with full force."
"I can't always control. When emotions are strong..." She looks at him desperately, "Diego, maybe you should forget about me."
"No." He kisses her. "We'll find a way out."
Act Four: The Storm
Growing conflict
Rumors about the "mermaid" are spreading throughout the town. Enrique gathers a group of fishermen: "This thing will scare off all the fish! We need to get rid of her!"
The priest Father Alfonso offers to perform an exorcism: "The devilish creature seduces young people!"
Diego's mother begs, "Son, leave this girl alone.
Diego defends Marina, but realizes that time is short. The full moon is in three days.
Disaster
A terrible storm rises at night, the strongest in a decade. A fishing boat with four men gets into trouble near the reefs. Among them is Diego's uncle, Pablo.
The Coast Guard can't get close because of the waves. People gather on the shore, helpless, watching as the boat crashes.
Marina hears screams. She stands on the rocks, torn apart: "If I help...
Diego is next to her: "Marina, they're going to die!"
She looks at him, then at the sea. Makes a decision.
Marina takes off her dress and jumps. In the air, her legs merge, turning into a huge, iridescent tail. She dives in.
Marina is completely transformed underwater — the gills on her neck open, her eyes glow, and she moves with incredible speed. She guides the fishermen away from the reefs, pushing the boat towards a safe channel.
On the shore, everyone can see: a creature with a tail rescues people.
When the fishermen are in shallow water, the Marina disappears into the waves. But there are already hundreds of people on the shore. They saw it.
Act Five: Choice
Hunting
The city is in hysterics. Some call Marina a savior, others a demon. Enrique shouts: "She lured us into the storm to appear like a hero!"
The crowd with torches goes to the Devil's Rocks.
Diego finds Marina in a cave. She is back in human form, but weak, trembling. "Transformation... it takes away strength... when it's not a full moon..."
"Marina, we need to leave. They're coming."
"Where? I can't live among people, Diego. They're afraid of me."
"Then the sea?"
She shakes her head, "If I come back now, before the full moon, I'll lose the chance. I'll forget everything. I'll forget what it means to love."
The crowd is getting closer. Diego closes the entrance to the cave, but Enrique and the other fishermen break through.
"Give her back, boy!"
"She saved your life!"
"She's evil!" — the priest shouts, waving the cross.
Marina comes out of the cave, proudly raising her head: "I won't hurt you. I'll leave."
She walks to the edge of the cliff. Diego grabs her hand: "Marina, no!"
"Diego, I can't live in a world where I'm hated."
"I don't hate."
"One thing is not enough." Tears on her face. "True love cannot exist in isolation. I need a world that accepts me. And this one...
She's about to jump, but suddenly Pablo, Diego's uncle, comes out of the crowd.: "Wait!"
He stands between Marina and the angry residents: "This one... young woman... Saved my life. To my friends. We would have drowned without her." He turns to the crowd: "Are you calling her a demon? Demons don't save lives!"
Gradually, other rescued fishermen join him. Then the fishermen's wives. Then the children. The crowd splits.
Old Senora Carla from the library says, "Legends are not always evil. Sometimes they remind us that the world is wider than we think."
Father Alfonso suddenly lowers the cross: "Maybe... We're too quick to judge what we don't understand."

Full moon
Midnight. The full moon is hanging over the sea. Marina stands on the edge of the cliff, Diego is next to her.
"Are you sure?" "What is it?" he asks.
"No," she answers honestly. "But I know I want to try. To live here with you, even if it means leaving the sea."
She takes a deep breath and... sings. The last siren song. Her voice carries over the water, shrill, beautiful, full of sadness and hope.
The waves rise and glow with phosphorescence. Dolphins jump out of the water, as if saying goodbye. Marina cries, but continues to sing.
When the song ends, the scars on her neck disappear. The hair loses its silvery shimmer, becoming ordinary human. She falls, and Diego catches her.
"Marina?"
She opens her eyes — now they are ordinary brown, without a glow: "I am... I can't hear the sea anymore. It's silent."
She sobs — the loss is huge. But Diego holds her, and gradually the tears subside.
"I've chosen," she whispers. "I chose you. I chose earth."
Epilogue
A year later
Marina works in a cafe with Diego. They're married. She still sings, but now her voice is ordinary, although beautiful. The tourists applaud, but no one goes crazy, no magic.
Sometimes Marina stands on the shore, looking at the sea with longing. Diego sees this and hugs her: "Are you bored?"
"Every day. It's a part of me that's dead." She turns to him.: "But the part that lives... happier."
Dolphins sometimes swim up to the shore when the Marina is there. She no longer understands their language, but she feels that they remember.
There's a statue of the Devil on the Rocks now.: a siren looking at the sea. Plaque: "In memory of those who choose love against nature. Marina, the Savior of 2024."
Marina and Diego stand in front of the statue. She takes his hand: "You know, I'm not sorry."
"Really?"
"Really. The sea was my home. But home is not where you were born. This is where your heart is."
They leave together, and the waves whisper softly on the shore — the farewell song of sirens.
