ACTS THREE. PAIN AND REBIRTH
Scene 1: Injury
Two weeks before the performance, during an intense rehearsal, an accident occurs.
Victoria performs a series of pirouettes in the center of the stage. This is a classic moment from Swan Lake, where Odette has to perform 32 consecutive turns on one leg - this is one of the most difficult elements in classical ballet, a technical miracle that requires tremendous strength, balance and concentration.
On the 28th turn, something breaks. Her body is out of rhythm. She's falling, but she's not falling like a dancer, she's falling like an ordinary person. She falls heavily, and a sound is heard - a sound like when something cracks.
Sergei and the others jump up from their seats. Victoria is lying on the stage, her face white with pain.
"Don't touch her," Sergei says. "Call an ambulance."
At the hospital, doctors perform an MRI scan. The diagnosis is terrible - a microfracture of the meniscus of the left knee. It's not critical, but it requires rest. At least two weeks of complete rest, and then without guarantees of full recovery.
The doctor, a young sports medic, looks at Victoria seriously.
"Ms. Romanova, I have to be honest. You are 45 years old. Your body doesn't recover as fast as it did when you were young. Two weeks is the minimum. But even if you start dancing after two weeks, the risk of injury returning is very high."
"What are you saying?"  Victoria asks.
"I'm saying that the performance can be canceled. Or postponed."
When Victoria leaves the hospital, she is greeted by Valentin.
"Victoria," he says, and there's genuine concern in his voice. "We will postpone the performance. For next season."
"No," Victoria says firmly.
"Victoria..."
"No, Valya. The performance is going according to plan. In may. I'm going to dance."
"It's dangerous.
" "Life is dangerous," Victoria replies. "Especially a life lived on stage."
Scene 2: Two Weeks in Hell
Victoria begins the toughest and most important training of her life. Every day is a pain. Every day is an attempt to cope with pain, treat it, and work with it.
She goes to a physical therapist every day. Her knee is wrapped in ice, then warm, then massaged. She takes anti-inflammatory drugs, which, according to the doctor, she should not have taken for ballet.
But besides physical pain, there is mental pain. Victoria falls into a period of doubt. What if she can't? What if her body fails her at the most important moment? What if she goes on stage and can't dance?
One night she calls Sergei.
"I can't," she says into the phone.
"You can," Sergei replies.
"Sergey, my knee... I do not know if it will hold up."
"He'll make it," Sergei says with such confidence that Victoria almost cries.
"How can you be sure?"
"Because I know you. I know you're capable of more than you think you are. Victoria, you are one of the greatest dancers in the history of ballet. Your body remembers how to dance. It has only forgotten how to listen to you when you tell it that it is impossible."
Victoria is crying into the phone.
"Listen," Sergei continues. "In May, I will be by your side. And we dance together like we always did. And nothing will happen. Because I won't let anything happen. I'll hold you."
After this conversation, Victoria stops doubting. She starts to believe.
The physiotherapist performs a miracle - in a week Victoria can walk without pain. After a week and a half, she can already dance a little. At the two-week mark, the doctor announces that the risk of re-injury has decreased to an acceptable level.
"But," he adds, "if you feel pain during the performance, you have to stop. Immediately. Otherwise, you risk not only your career, but also your health."
Victoria nods. She agrees to these terms.
Scene 3: The last rehearsals
Victoria spends the last rehearsals with Sergey before the performance. This time, every move is performed with full dedication, without fear, without doubt. They dance as one whole - two parts of one organism, two voices in one symphony.
Anna watches the rehearsals from the edge of the stage. She sees Victoria and Sergey dancing, and she realizes that such perfection is not yet available to her. This is perfection that comes only with age, with experience, with a life lived.
One day, after a rehearsal, Victoria takes Anna's hand.
"Anna, I want to tell you something that I have never told anyone. That's why I chose Sergei as a partner for my last performance."
Anna listens attentively.
"Sergey was my first love. My only love. I turned him down because I was sure that dancing was all I needed in life. And I was partly right. Dancing has given me everything - fame, recognition, traveling the world. But he also took away my family, my children, and the everyday happiness that ordinary people experience."
"Are you sorry?"  Anna asks.
"No," Victoria says. "Because my life's journey is my life's journey. I couldn't have chosen any other way. But I want you to choose differently. You are young, ambitious, and talented. You can reach heights. But please don't give up your life for the stage. Leave room for love. Leave room for the family. Dancing is great, but that's not all."
Anna nods, and Victoria sees that these words have entered her heart.

ACTS FOUR. THE LAST DANCE
Scene 1: The day of the play
Morning of May. The sun rises over Moscow, as usual, without knowing that something extraordinary will happen on this day.
Victoria wakes up in her apartment. Her knee hurts a little, a common pain she's learned to ignore. She gets up, goes to the bathroom, then into the living room, where her ballet costume lies on the couch - a white, incredibly beautiful Odette dress decorated with feathers and crystals.
She takes the dress and hugs it to her. This dress is her life. She had danced in it hundreds of times. She would dance in it for the last time.
In the theater, in the dressing room, Victoria is getting ready. The makeup artist applies makeup - white, clean, with tear lines that make her look like a sad bird. The hairdresser puts her hair in a perfect bun. The costume designer helps her put on her dress.
When Victoria sees herself in the mirror, she sees not the 45-year-old woman she is, but the 25-year-old prima ballerina she was 20 years ago. Time somehow recedes back, and during the performance she will be young.
A bell sounds - a five-minute warning. Victoria gets up and goes to the stage. In the hallway, she meets Sergei, dressed in a black Prince Siegfried suit. He looks handsome, young, despite his age.
They look at each other in silence.
"Are you ready?" - Sergey asks.
"No," Victoria replies. "But it doesn't matter. We're dancing anyway."
They take each other's hands. Together they walk to the stage entrance.
Scene 2: The First Act
The curtain rises. The light falls on the lake. The scene shows a lake landscape - swans swimming in the water, cypresses leaning over the shore, the moon hanging high in the sky.
And Victoria steps into the middle of the stage. Her first move is a simple step, but this step is her whole life. She moves around the stage like a real bird, like a swan enchanted by the witch Odile, chaining him to the lake.
In the first act, Odette meets Siegfried. The famous adagio takes place between them - a slow, graceful dance in which they tell a love story. Victoria is dancing like never before. Every move is perfect. Every look is a whole story. When she dances, it seems that she doesn't touch the ground, that her body is just a reflection of her soul.
Sergey supports her with such tenderness and strength at the same time. There are no mistakes between them, no moments of uncertainty. They dance like two organisms fused into one.
When the first act ends, the audience stands up and gives a standing ovation. But Victoria will not hear these applause - she is all in the role, all in Odette, all in the pain and sadness of this character.
Scene 3: The Second Act
The second act begins in daylight. The scene shifts to the royal palace. Siegfried is given a ball where he must choose a bride from four princesses. But instead of them, Odile appears - the black swan, the daughter of a witch who seduces Siegfried.
Anna enters the stage as Odile. She's gorgeous-energetic, seductive, dangerous. Her technique is perfect. But Victoria sees something that Anna doesn't see yet-she sees the depth that only comes with life experience.
However, at this moment, when Odile is dancing her main solo - 32 pirouettes in a row - something unexpected happens. Anna falls.
On the 18th pirouette, her left foot slips. She's losing her balance. She falls right on the stage, right in front of the royal court.
The hall quiets down. It is a rare, humiliating sight to see a ballerina fall during the main solo, during the most difficult element.
But Anna gets up. No help, no tears. She gets up and completes her dance, despite the fall, despite the shame. When she finishes, the audience gives her a special ovation-not for perfection, but for bravery.
Victoria, waiting for her moment, sees this. And she's proud of Anna. She sees that Anna has learned the main lesson-not perfection, but the ability to stand up and continue.
The third act is the finale. Odile leaves, and Odette appears. The moment of truth is coming. Siegfried realizes that he has been deceived. He's looking for Odette. They're dating. He begs her forgiveness. But the curse cannot be lifted. The only way to escape is death.
Victoria performs the final adagio. This is a slow, carefree dance in which Odette's whole life is her love, her pain, her loneliness. When she dances, fifty people in the theater cry.
And now comes the final moment. Odette must jump into the lake, because the curse can only be broken by death. Victoria rises at the edge of the stage, at the edge of the "lake".
She looks down into the abyss. She looks at Sergei, her Siegfried. There are tears in his eyes. He holds out his hand, but he knows he can't hold it. Their love is too great to be caught in the living world. It belongs only to art, only to dance.
Victoria jumps.
And when she jumps, a miracle happens. Her knee doesn't hurt. Her body doesn't betray her. She flies across the stage like a real bird, like a real swan, and lands perfectly.
The music stops. The lights go out. Odette is dead, but she is free.
Scene 4: The Curtain
The curtain begins to fall. And when he has almost closed the stage, he rises again. Victoria and Sergey come out to bow.
At first, the audience is silent. Then the noise begins - not just applause, but a standing ovation. People get up from their seats. People are crying. People are screaming. It's not just applause, it's love, recognition, and respect.
Victoria steps forward and the viewer sees her face. Her cheeks are wet with tears. She looks at the hall, at the sea of people who have come to see her for the last time. She looks at the front row, where her mother and sister are sitting. Her mother is holding a bouquet of flowers and crying.
Sergei takes Victoria's hand and they bow together. It's not a dance anymore - it's just a moment between two people who have lived their lives together, even though they haven't been together all these years.
Victoria drops into a deep curtsy, which is what a ballerina does at the end of her career, when she thanks the theater, thanks the audience, and thanks art for giving her life.
When she gets up, the curtain falls again. This time, he is lifted up once more. And one more time. And again.
After seven minutes of applause, the curtain finally closes, and Victoria knows that her career is over. Not because her body can't dance anymore, but because she decided to complete it with dignity, at a moment of perfection when people remember her as a queen.

THE EPILOGUE. revival
Scene 1: After the performance
In the dressing room, Victoria is sitting in a theatrical dressing gown, her makeup smeared with sweat and tears. Her costume is no longer white, but grayish from the dust of the stage. She looks tired, devastated, but there is something new shining in her eyes - clarity, peace, meaning.
Sergei enters. He's in the dressing room too, his hair damp with sweat.
"You were great," he says, and this simple recognition means more than thousands of critical reviews.
Victoria gets up and hugs him. They stand together, two dancers, two artists, two people whose lives have been defined by dancing.
"Thank you," Victoria says. "For being with me. For dancing with me the last time."
"Thank you," Sergey replies. "For asking me. For giving me the opportunity to dance with you again."
They know that this is the end of their dance together. Sergey will return to Switzerland tomorrow. They might never see each other again. But what they have created together in these four months will remain forever.
Scene 2: Anna's Visit
The next day, Anna arrives at Victoria's office in the theater.
"I saw your performance," Victoria says to Anna. "You fell, but you got up and carried on. It was more perfect than any error-free performance."
Anna is crying. "I thought I ruined the play. I thought people would remember the fall."
"No," Victoria says. "People will remember your strength. They'll remember how you got up. It's a real ballet, Anna. Not technique, not perfection. This is humanity."
Victoria takes Anna by both hands.
"I want to ask you one thing. I remain in the theater as a ballet teacher. Senior teacher and mentor of young dancers. I want you to be my first student. I want to teach you not only dance, but also life. I want to help you avoid the mistakes I've made."
Anna nods, her eyes shining with tears.
“yeah. Please."
Scene 3: A New Life
In a month. Victoria is in the rehearsal room of the theater, surrounded by young dancers. They are working on the basic elements of classical ballet.
But when Victoria teaches, she doesn't just teach movements. She tells stories. She talks about every ballet, every character, and what it means to be a ballerina, not only physically, but also emotionally.
Anna is sitting in the foreground, listening to every word.
"Positions," says Victoria. "The first position. This is the beginning. That's all you have when you start. But from this position you can create a whole world. The whole ballet starts from here."
She shows the first position - heels together, socks apart, hands in elegant relaxation.
"It feels like life," Victoria continues. "You start with nothing. But if you build correctly, if you are true to your form and your art, you can become anything."
In the evening, when the rehearsal ends, Victoria is alone on stage. She puts on her ballet shoes-not the new ones that are used in performances, but the old, worn shoes she's been dancing in for years.
She gets into the first position. Then the second one. Then she starts moving slowly around the stage, performing simple movements - the ones she started with as a child.
Her knee doesn't hurt. Her body feels pain, but it's a good pain, the pain of someone who knows their strength, the pain of someone who has accepted their boundaries and learned to live with them.
She dances for herself. Not for the public, not for critics, not for fame. Just for myself. And in this dance she finds what she has been looking for all her life - simplicity, truth, meaning.
Scene 4: The Epilogue one year later
A year has passed. Victoria is now known not only as the prima ballerina of the past, but also as one of the best teachers of the Bolshoi Theater. Her students win contests, get leading roles, and become stars.
Anna has just been cast as Odette in the new production of Swan Lake. When Victoria hears about this, she cries, but these are tears of joy.
On Victoria's birthday, which she celebrated with her family - with her mother, sister, nephews and nieces - she receives a letter from Switzerland. From Sergey.
In the letter, he writes: Dear Victoria, I watched the video of your last rehearsal with the young dancers. You dance no less beautifully than before. Perhaps even more beautiful, because now you dance not for the public, but for art. I'm proud of you. And I'm grateful that we danced together for the last time. It was my last dance. Thank you. With love, Sergey."
Victoria reads the letter and smiles. She understands that she has found what she was looking for - not fame, not perfection, not eternal youth. She found the meaning. She found a way to serve the arts even after her own days on stage were over.
The final scene: The stage of the theater at dusk
Victoria stands on the empty stage of the Bolshoi Theatre. The theater is closed for maintenance. There is no one but her. The light rays of sunset fall through the windows of the theater, creating patterns of light and shadow.
She gets into the first position. Slowly, gracefully, she begins her last personal dance. She dances for herself, for her life, for all the decisions she has made.
When the dance ends, she stops in the center of the stage and looks up at the chandelier of the theater, at the light that has illuminated this sacred stage for more than a hundred years.
"Thank you," she whispers to the theater, to all the art, to everything that gave her life.
The lights go out. The scene darkens. But somewhere in the darkness, music can be heard - the same music of "Swan Lake", the melody that haunted Victoria all her life, the melody that now sings in her heart.
And in this music, in this sound, you can hear her whole life - all the love, all the pain, all the beauty, all the sacrifice, all the joy, everything - her last dance.


The
Last Dance is a story about how to find meaning in life when the path that has defined you all your life is coming to an end. This is a story about the love of art, about personal sacrifice, about growth, about forgiveness, and about how to pass the light on to the next generation.
The film explores the eternal question: what remains when fame is gone? The answer is humanity, wisdom, the ability to serve, the ability to love, the ability to find meaning not in applause, but in art itself and in life, which is beyond the stage.
Victoria Romanova is a symbol of each of us who is faced with the end of an era, with the need to rethink ourselves, with the challenge of starting a new chapter in life. Her story shows that the end can be the beginning, that the death of one life can be the birth of another, and that the beauty of the human spirit lies not in perfection, but in the ability to adapt, grow and continue dancing, even when the music is changing.
$$)
) AS loc(locale, title, description, plot_summary)
ON TRUE;

WITH m AS (
    INSERT INTO content_service.movies
        (original_title, release_date, duration, rating, country_id, created_at, updated_at)
        VALUES
            ($$The Immortality Code$$, '2023-08-14', 8340, 8.6, 10, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP, CURRENT_TIMESTAMP)
