        ('en_EN', $$The Underwater Circus$$, $$Ocean creatures create a dazzling circus on the ocean floor. Its star acrobat—a dolphin—dreams of performing on the surface.$$, $$Part One: The birth of a dream
At a depth of one and a half thousand meters of the Pacific Ocean, where sunlight barely penetrates through the water and creates a shimmering twilight, there is an underwater microcosm of extraordinary beauty. Coral reefs formed natural arenas and amphitheaters, dissected by crevasses and decorated with amazing formations. It was here, in this underwater palace, that the most unusual idea that could arise in the animal kingdom was born — the idea of creating a circus.
The initiator was a wise and charismatic octopus named Octavius. His age was as impressive as his intelligence—forty-three years in the octopus kingdom means he has lived a long, experience-filled life. Octavius traveled all over the seas, saw human port cities, and casually watched ship performances through glass portholes. One day, he fished out a rusty cinema projector — a miracle of human technology, thrown into the sea — and for a week, continuously studying it, he understood the essence of theatrical art.
"Why should only people have fun?" — he told his brothers. "Why can't we create our own performance, our own world of wonders?"
Octavius mastered the art of juggling, which he developed to perfection. All eight of its tentacles moved in synchronized harmony, lifting pearls, pebbles, and glowing jellyfish into the water, causing them to spin in complex patterns. It was mesmerizing, almost magical. The audience, who saw this performance for the first time, hung in the water, fascinated by the artistry of the octopus.
But soon Octavius realized that one artist would not be able to make a circus great. He needed a troupe.
Part Two: Collecting Stars
The first person Octavius invited was a young dolphin named Splash. Splash wasn't just young and energetic—he was an acrobatic genius. His silvery body moved with a grace and precision that seemed completely impossible for such a large creature. Splash could perform a triple somersault in the narrow space of the coral maze, passing through rings of intertwined algae that were barely thicker than his own body. He created waves of perfection, his every leap was well thought out, every turn calculated.
When Octavius invited him to perform in the circus, the young dolphin laughed at first. "The circus? Under water? Who's going to watch this?"
But Octavius was convincing. "Remember how you feel when you perfect your trick. It's a delight, right? Imagine now how this delight will increase a thousandfold if it is shared by thousands of viewers watching and admiring you."
Splash agreed.
Following the dolphin, the troupe included seahorses, tightrope walkers - four graceful creatures with spiraled tails that soared with exquisite grace along the "ropes" of algae stretched between the corals. They moved so slowly and carefully that every movement looked like ballet, like an ancient ritual dance. The audience often forgot to breathe while watching their performances.
Then came the strongman sharks, an unusual group of young sharks who, instead of hunting, decided to use their power and muscles for artistic expression. They lifted huge rocks, carried whole fragments of coral, creating living monuments to their power. Their performances were a symbol of power, respect and nobility.
And, of course, there were the clown fish, a whole bunch of orange- and white—colored creatures who possessed an innate sense of humor and comedy. They caught each other, created intricate chases, and fell into the water in the most comical positions, making the entire theater shudder with laughter. Their art was based on the understanding that funny is a universal language that everyone understands.
Part Three: The Golden Age of Underwater Theater
Soon, the news about the circus spread across the ocean. Every evening, when the light from the surface finally disappeared and complete darkness fell, the performance began. Octavius activated the luminescent organisms that he had tamed and trained to glow at certain moments, creating vivid stage lighting.
The performances attracted audiences from all over the Pacific Ocean. Whales swam from afar, hovering over the theater and making admiring sounds. The sea turtles slowly took their places on the coral bleachers. Fish, sharks, rays, octopuses — they all came to experience a night of wonder and artistry.
Each performance lasted three hours and included numbers of varying difficulty. It started with light comic sketches of clown fish, which created a good mood. Then came the tightrope walkers with their ballet grace. The strongman sharks performed in the middle when the energy was at its peak. And the finale was always Splash, with its incredible acrobatic performances that left the audience in a state of ecstatic stupor.
Octavius juggled between the numbers, commented on what was happening, was the director, the host and the main actor at the same time. His authority was unshakeable, his decisions were respected, and his vision was clear.
But not everyone in the underwater troupe was happy.
Part Four: The Border of Worlds
Splash, despite his success, felt an unquenchable thirst inside himself. Every evening, after the performance, when the audience scattered across the seas, a young dolphin swam up to the surface. There, at dusk, he saw the lights of ships, saw people standing on the deck, saw another world — the world of air, land, heavenly bodies.
"Why should we perform only for ourselves?"  He asked Octavius one day. "People have created circuses, theaters, they have fun. What if we could show them our world? What if we could help them understand the beauty of the ocean?"
The other artists took the idea as crazy. The tightrope-walking seahorses bobbed their heads. "Dolphins can't stay out of the water for long, Splash. It would kill us. Our lungs are not adapted."
Even Octavius, usually open to new ideas, looked skeptical. "The boundary between worlds does not just exist, young friend. People and animals live in different elements. It's a law of nature."
But Splash didn't give up. Every day he thought about it, dreamed about it, imagined himself performing in front of people, overcoming barriers between species, between worlds.
Part Five: A traveler from distant seas
One day, when there was a performance, an old turtle swam into the theater. Her shell has been pitted for years, covered with seagrasses and shells, as if she were a living reef. Her eyes shone with ancient wisdom. It was Selena, a black sea turtle that had traveled all over the oceans of the world for over a hundred years.
Selena sat next to Octavius and watched the performance. After the lights went out and the actors left, she stayed with the director.
"I've seen many wonders in my travels," she said, her voice low but filled with authority. "I saw people. I saw their cities on the shores. And I've seen something amazing - places where people keep marine animals and let them perform in front of other people. They call these places oceanariums."
Octavius leaned forward. "Tell me more details."
"There are huge pools filled with seawater in these places, right in people's buildings. Dolphins, whales, sea lions — they all perform there in front of crowds of people who stand behind thick glass and watch. People pay money to see it. And the animals don't die — they get food, medical care, they live well."
"But this is captivity," Octavius objected.
"Maybe," Selena agreed. "But it's also a bridge between worlds. This is an opportunity to show people how wonderful we are, what beauty lies beneath the waves. Maybe when people see beauty, they will want to protect it instead of destroying it."
Part Six: Preparing for the big jump
Splash heard the conversation. When Selena described the tours of marine animals in human cities, the young dolphin realized that his dream was not impossible. It wasn't a fantasy, but a reality that already existed.
He went to Octavius.
"I know it sounds crazy," Splash began. "But Selena told me about the places where we could perform. About oceanariums. Director, can you imagine how many people would be able to see our circus and understand what kind of world exists underwater?"
Octavius was silent for a long time. Then he said: "It's not just a question of performance, Splash. It's a question of who we are. About our responsibility to our species, to the ocean."
"I know," Splash replied. "But I also know that people are destroying our house because they don't know what's here. If we show them, maybe they will change?"
Octavius looked at the young dolphin for a long time. Then he nodded.
"Okay. We'll try. But only for touring, only for a certain time. And only with volunteers."
Almost all the members of the troupe agreed. Only some of the seahorses decided to stay, fearing change. But most of them, especially Splash, clownfish, and strongman sharks, were ready.
Part Seven: The first performance on the surface
They arrived at a huge aquarium on the Pacific coast of a major city. The pools were spacious, the water was checked and certified by specialists, and the filtration system worked perfectly. People have prepared an outdoor performance, under the stars.
When the performance began, thousands of people entered the theater. They occupied seats around a huge pool, where artificial lighting shone.
And then the clown fish began their act. People laughed — real laughter, lively, sincere. Then the tightrope walkers came out, and the people fell silent, speechless before the grace of these creatures. The strongman sharks received a standing ovation. But when Splash came out and performed his first triple somersault in the huge pool, holy silence reigned in the theater.
For the first time, people really saw not an isolated animal in the pool, but an artist, a master, a genius in his field. They saw art, pure and genuine. When Splash completed his final somersault and emerged from the water, spray flew into the crowd, people jumped up from their seats, letting out shouts of delight.
The ovation lasted fifteen minutes.
Epilogue: Bridge between Worlds
The first performance was followed by the rest. The underwater circus tour became a sensation. People came from all over the world to see this miracle. The media covered the events, children's schools organized excursions, and scientists studied the behavior of animals and their artistic abilities.
But the most important thing happened outside the theater. After people saw the beauty of the underwater world, captured in the performances of dolphins, octopuses and other animals, organizations began to be created to protect marine ecosystems. People started demanding stricter laws against ocean pollution. The children asked their parents not to use plastic. Public opinion has shifted towards protecting marine life.
Splash realized that his dream had come true not just as an artistic achievement, but as a mission. He became a bridge between two worlds — the world of humans and the world of animals, the world of air and the world of water.
The underwater circus has now traveled all over the world, crossing continents and cultures, showing people the beauty and grandeur of what exists beneath the waves. And every time Splash made his jump, when Octavius juggled in the flickering light, when the clown fish made the crowd laugh, they conveyed one simple message: the ocean is a miracle, and it deserves to be preserved.
Selena, an old turtle traveler, often sailed to the theater and watched the performances. And every time she smiled, seeing how her long-held dream of a bridge between worlds had finally become a reality.
